<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1436,289,566]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,351,325,350]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Introduction</emphasis>
: Eight species of 
<taxonomicName box="[572,715,325,349]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Neochavesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[572,715,325,349]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Neochavesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are now known (
<bibRefCitation author="Schneider, S. A. &amp; LaPolla, J. S." box="[921,1236,325,349]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="57 - 82" refId="ref60232" refString="Schneider, S. A. &amp; LaPolla, J. S. (2011) Systematics of the mealybug tribe Xenococcini (Hemiptera: Coccoidea: Pseudococcidae), with a discussion of trophobiotic associations with Acropyga Roger ants. Systematic Entomology, 36, 57 - 82." type="journal article" year="2011">Schneider &amp; LaPolla, 2011</bibRefCitation>
) and adult males have been described for two of them (
<taxonomicName authority="(Balachowsky)" baseAuthorityName="Balachowsky" box="[597,920,361,385]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Chavesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caldasiae">
<emphasis box="[597,740,361,385]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">N. caldasiae</emphasis>
(Balachowsky)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[938,1022,361,385]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="55.[151,250,1945,1968]" captionTargetBox="[225,1400,158,1939]" captionTargetId="figure-63@55.[151,1436,99,1990]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 19. Neochavesia caldasiae (Balachowsky). Adult male. Where A = hair-like setae; C = loculate pores, J = dorsal view of poster end of abdomen, and L = ventral view of abdomen. For other labels, see under Materials and methods: conventions. (Modified after Williams, 2004a)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5250088" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5250088/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Williams" authorityName="Williams (Williams" authorityYear="2004" box="[1091,1325,361,385]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Neochavesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lapollai">
<emphasis box="[1091,1213,361,385]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">N. lapollai</emphasis>
Williams
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1343,1427,361,385]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="56.[151,250,1906,1929]" captionTargetBox="[158,1433,241,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-64@56.[150,1436,193,1885]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURE 20. Neochavesia lapollai Williams. Adult male. Where A = hair-like setae; J = dorsal view of posterior end of abdomen; L = ventral view of abdomen and M = claw. For other labels, see under Materials and methods: conventions. (Modified after Williams, 2004a)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5250090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5250090/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, D. J." box="[158,348,397,421]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="2883 - 2899" refId="ref60867" refString="Williams, D. J. (2004 a) A synopsis of the subterranean mealybug genus Neochavesia Williams and Granara de Willink (Hemiptera: Pseudococcidae: Rhizoecinae). Journal of Natural History, 38 (22), 2883 - 2899." type="journal article" year="2004">Williams, 2004a</bibRefCitation>
)). The adult male of a third species is described below. The adult females of all the known species possess well-developed protruding anal lobes, and an anal ring without cells and placed well forward of the apex of the abdomen. A generic diagnosis and a key based on the adult females are given in 
<bibRefCitation author="Schneider, S. A. &amp; LaPolla, J. S." pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="57 - 82" refId="ref60232" refString="Schneider, S. A. &amp; LaPolla, J. S. (2011) Systematics of the mealybug tribe Xenococcini (Hemiptera: Coccoidea: Pseudococcidae), with a discussion of trophobiotic associations with Acropyga Roger ants. Systematic Entomology, 36, 57 - 82." type="journal article" year="2011">Schneider and LaPolla (2011)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1436,289,566]" box="[199,1123,541,566]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">For a morphological diagnosis of the males of this genus, see key to genera above.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
